 be manual or automatic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Turn off the lights
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Lock the door (this may be manual or automatic)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Appendix: An Simple Example Implementation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This example is purely to show how the system could work with the proposal
 above, it is not to be treated as part of the proposal itself and it's
 likely that the technical solution we use to address the proposal will
 not be this example implementation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Keys/Access Cards
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
RFID lock on the door.
 Access Cards and Keys are both RFID cards.
 When an RFID card is scanned the system looks up the user and if they are
 a Keyholder then it lets them in; otherwise if they are a Access Cardholder
 it only lets them in if the space is Open.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Opening
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When a Keyholder enters the space they flick the Space Opening Switch (like
 we had at rideride) which marks the space as Open and announces the opening
 to Twitter/IRC/etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Closing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the last Keyholder leaves the space they reset the Space Opening Switch,
 announcing that the space is closed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There may be a Watchdog timer that automatically Closes the space if the
 door has not been opened in at least 2 hours unless someone inside the
 space presses a button.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Problems with this implementation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
No indication of how long the space will be open for
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
This could be addressed by using a potentiometer or similar combined with
 an LCD display instead of a switch as the Space Opening Switch; this could
 also address the "having to kick people out" issue too.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Fails in a power cut
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
A key override in the RFID lock is desirable, but the people who have access
 to this key should be severely limited (e.g.
 just the Trustees) since it doesn't involve any authentication.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Is software based and potentially hackable
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
May be best to run this off of a non-networked Pi that is locked securely;
 though doing so makes it harder to approve new Access Cardholder/Keyholders
 quickly
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The RFID lock may not be sufficiently strong for an external door.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
This could be solved by using a heavy duty mechanical combination lock and
 giving the code to all Keyholders.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The combo lock needs to be able to be left in an unlocked state otherwise
 Access Cardholder would not be able to gain access to the space when it
 is Open.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
